        "title": "java PasswordAuthentication security",
        "body": "<p>I am working on a Java program which record data from sensors and send me the result by email (the computer is far from my office).<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>    Properties props = new Properties();\n    props.put(\"mail.smtp.host\", HOST);\n    props.put(\"mail.smtp.port\", \"587\");\n    props.put(\"mail.smtp.starttls.enable\", \"true\");\n    props.put(\"mail.smtp.ssl.enable\", \"false\");\n\n    Session session = Session.getInstance(props, new javax.mail.Authenticator() {\n        protected PasswordAuthentication getPasswordAuthentication() {\n            return new PasswordAuthentication(LOGIN, PASSWORD);\n        }\n    });\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>So I put my login/password non-encrypted in my code. It works but it is not safe because anyone can uncompress the jar file and find my login/password. What could be the best approach? Even if I use an encrypted external file, I have to provided the key to decrypt the file.<\/p>\n",
